:"1380–Overleden","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1370–1485":"1370–1485","1374–1430":"1374–1430","1305–Male":"1305–Overleden","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1345":"1345","1399":"1399","1485":"1485","1353":"1353","1430":"1430","about 1345":"circa 1345","Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Schotland","Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Schotland","Loudoun Castle, Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Schotland","Loudon, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"about 1345–":"about 1345–Deceased","1337–Male":"1337–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1345–Female":"1345–Deceased","1350–1430":"1350–1430","1353–Male":"1353–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1370–1485":"1370–1485","1374–1430":"1374–1430","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1345":"1345","1399":"1399","1485":"1485","1353":"1353","1430":"1430","about 1345":"about 1345","Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudoun Castle, Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudon, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Berkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Barclay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."]},{"name":"Berkley","meanings":["English: variant of   Berkeley  . Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): assimilated form of   Berkowitz  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret de Berkeley was born about 1345, in Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland as the daughter of Sir Hugh de Berkeley - Third Lord of Kilbirnie. She married Sir George Campbell in 1372, in Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland."},"et":{"about 1345–":"umbes 1345–Surnud","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1350–1430":"1350–1430","1353–Male":"1353–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1370–1485":"1370–1485","1374–1430":"1374–1430","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1374":"1374","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1345":"1345","1399":"1399","1485":"1485","1353":"1353","1430":"1430","about 1345":"umbes 1345","Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilbirnie, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudoun Castle, Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland","Loudon, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Loudoun, Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1345–":"noin 1345–Kuollut","1337–Male":"1337–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1345–Female":"1345–Kuollut","1350–1430":"1350–1430","1353–Male":"1353–Kuollut","1380–Male":"1380–Kuollut","1345–1399":"1345–139